			<div class="content" id="post-content-3119765">
									

<p>If you have a sandbox, the work you do isn't wasted. You have a copy of everything you write, so you can continue to make changes to articles that get deleted. So, the burden on the author is not high enough to justify imposing a responsibility on voters.</p>
<p>Additionally, the rating system can only properly serve as the site's quality control with a high volume of votes. This is the main reason why the site doesn't really impose responsibilities on voters &#8212; the more steps any process has, the fewer people that do it. Odds are, under your system, you wouldn't get much more feedback, just fewer votes.</p>
<p>It would also be a fucking devil to actually enforce. Lots of voters only interact with the site very casually, and writing up everyone who assumes they can just click a button and be on their way would likely comprise a very big task for staff that, frankly, have better things to do.</p>
<p>If you feel like you're not getting sufficient feedback, you might want to apply some of the techniques found <a href="/how-to-get-good-feedback">here</a>.</p>

