			<div class="content" id="post-content-3149680">
									

<p>Echoing this sentiment here. Considering how few downvotes it takes to get your article deleted compounded with how hard feedback is to come by, the threshold seems to me unreasonably high. I've mostly tried to follow the procedure and advice outlined by the guide linked to below, read most if not all essential writing guides, been quite particular about mine academic style and background research, and spent half-a-year just devouring articles before even trying to make one of mine own&#8230; and still it felt incredibly hard to come by any feedback. And the goes especially considering the attention brought to how important that is to get.</p>
<p>Also, this community is very harsh. For good reason I suppose, considering your history. However, it can make it hard for beginners to even get off ground, and has a high risk if killing one's drive, even if said author likely would've have written a good article given enough patience and guidance. As it is now, it kind of feels like you only have a chance of getting anywhere if you're one of the more established authors, and that it's rather futile to try if you aren't among those select few.</p>
<p><strong>What I would like to see changed</strong> is thus: If an author has posted article in the negatives but, on the discussion page, commits to changing the article based on the feedback received therein, it'd be nice to see that author given the benefit of the doubt before removing their article. Extend the cutoff line for deletion beyond 24 hours (considering how many of us have jobs, studies, families, ailments etc. that requires so much of our time) for that article. While I'm well aware you don't want to see the site's quality deteriorate, the way it is now just feels like you're given too short a time window and, overall, forbiddingly harsh. (I've always been of the &quot;revise, not remove&quot; camp over on Wikipedia, so mine opinion is also informed by that philosophy.)</p>
<p><strong>EDIT:</strong> Or another idea is to use the &quot;Review Attention Levels&quot; system developed by the DE branch. <a href="http://scp-int.wikidot.com/review-attention-levels" target="_blank">We use a very similar system over at the INT branch</a> and find that it's working out really well, especially in conjunction with our dedicated Review Team.</p>

