<p>the way it is now just feels like you're given too short a time window and, overall, forbiddingly harsh.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>How much of an extension were you thinking here? I'd admittedly a little iffy on this, since given the sheer number of things that get deleted every day (here's the current deletion thread: <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/forum/t-2302957/deletions-44:ar-logh-qoy-lu-pu">http://www.scp-wiki.net/forum/t-2302957/deletions-44:ar-logh-qoy-lu-pu</a>) there's a chance that there might be a pileup of things in the negatives and there's no guarantee (or requirement) that those who downvote will reread and revote after revisions.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Or another idea is to use the &quot;Review Attention Levels&quot; system developed by the DE branch. We use a very similar system over at the INT branch and find that it's working out really well, especially in conjunction with our dedicated Review Team.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>How big is your review team, and how often are new pages put up for review attention, say, weekly? I'm all for having a dedicated hub system for figuring out what needs to be reviewed and at what priority level, provided we have the staff/experienced reviewer manpower to address it.</p>

