			<div class="content" id="post-content-3158926">
									

<p>I kind of feel the same here. Getting a review is very difficult. Just one example: even when there are answers with precious advice on the forum, and you want to go deeper asking questions about the received critique, it's not unusual that there's no answer (which is probably due to the forum having no notification system, I guess).</p>
<p>For the article I posted on the mainlist, I actually used the 24-hour courtesy period to get the most feedback possible. A very ill way to do that, I think; I should have gotten those feedback <em>before</em> that. More: I should have received this precise feedback: &quot;this is in <em>no way</em> ready for the mainlist, what are you thinking?&quot;. Which didn't happen.</p>
<p><em>E.g.</em>, my article was downvoted by people that didn't even read it, because the first dowvotes came in a timespan too short to actually have read it. So the article was <em>so obviously not ready</em> that you could tell at a glance, and yet nobody told me<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-883706-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-883706-1')">1</a></sup>.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>the sheer number of things that get deleted every day (here's the current deletion thread: <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/forum/t-2302957/deletions-44:ar-logh-qoy-lu-pu">http://www.scp-wiki.net/forum/t-2302957/deletions-44:ar-logh-qoy-lu-pu</a>)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>That was enlightening, and made me think.</p>
<p>I mean, how is that possible? That shouldn't even happen in the first place.</p>
<p>Let me clarify with an analogy: suppose this was a factory, and a lot of finished products<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-883706-2" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-883706-2')">2</a></sup> are <em>so defective</em> they need to be scrapped: there's obviously a huge problem in the production line (in this case, in the review process). In a similar real world scenario, the supervisor would get so angry that many heads would roll.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Extend the cutoff line for deletion beyond 24 hours (considering how many of us have jobs, studies, families, ailments etc. that requires so much of our time) for that article.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Not to mention the fact that users live in different time zones, which utterly reduces the courtesy countdown.</p>
<p>I really like the 24-hour courtesy period, I find it to be very kind towards authors; when it happened to me, although it hurt, I felt respected as an author. But, as <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/nederbird" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2854162); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2854162&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1499609752" alt="Nederbird" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2854162)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/nederbird" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2854162); return false;">Nederbird</a></span> pointed out, it may not be enough &#8212; I am not talking about the mere timespan, but about the process itself.</p>
<p>Example: an author posts an article, but unfortunately vote falls below deletion threshold, and now the author has 24 hours to fix it. Ok, fair enough. But</p>
<blockquote>
<p>there's no guarantee (or requirement) that those who downvote will reread and revote after revisions.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>So, is it really useful, then?</p>
<p>To answer that we first need data. <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1404533&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1499609752" alt="Zyn" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1404533)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;">Zyn</a></span>, or another staff member, is there a statistics on the percentage of articles that survive the 24-hour period? That would help discuss the matter properly.</p>
<div class="footnotes-footer">
<div class="title">Footnotes</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-883706-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-883706-1')">1</a>. I got many good critiques on it, but I am still unsure, because none of them was pointing out to any obvious huge problem.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-883706-2"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-883706-2')">2</a>. Mainlist articles are finished products.</div>
</div>

