			<div class="content" id="post-content-3161108">
									

<p>My responses:</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>it's not unusual that there's no answer (which is probably due to the forum having no notification system, I guess).</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Authors should ask for replies if they're not getting them. I get a ton of requests every week in PM and on chat, and it's hard for me to keep track of all my ongoing conversations as new drafts come in and I reply to those. Feel free to send a PM to a reviewer if they haven't replied to a post of yours. If they react rudely, let a staff member know.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>More: I should have received this precise feedback: &quot;this is in no way ready for the mainlist, what are you thinking?&quot;. Which didn't happen.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Sometimes inexperienced people give feedback on the forums/chat and people dive into the mainsite before a draft is ready&#8212;we try to avoid this by making crit quality expectations higher in the forums, but that results in a lot less feedback and a lot more burnout by quality critters.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>E.g., my article was downvoted by people that didn't even read it, because the first dowvotes came in a timespan too short to actually have read it.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>People can and will downvote a piece without reading all of it. They're not obligated to finish the piece if they didn't enjoy the part they did read; authors here write for an audience who consumes these articles as entertainment, after all.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I mean, how is that possible? That shouldn't even happen in the first place.</p>
<p>there's obviously a huge problem in the production line (in this case, in the review process). In a similar real world scenario, the supervisor would get so angry that many heads would roll.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Well&#8230; no one's paid for the work they do on the site, not even staff members. People write here as a hobby, not as a job (although staff work is essentially an unpaid job. I put it on my IRL resume as volunteer experience).</p>
<p>Everything here is done as part of a hobby, and there is and has always been a lot more people who want to write for the site than those who want to review for the site and furthermore, actively give good reviews. And there always have been people who don't want to get reviews because they think their stuff is fine as is, they don't want to put a ton of effort into fixing something that they wrote for fun, they're unhappy when their work is criticized, they didn't read the guidelines carefully when starting, etc. I don't know how many such members are on the site, but they vastly outnumber our experienced writers.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Example: an author posts an article, but unfortunately vote falls below deletion threshold, and now the author has 24 hours to fix it. Ok, fair enough. But [&#8230;] is it really useful, then?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Another reason why I'm not sure about extending the deadline, since either way the author has, well, a deadline. I've always felt that the deletion vote was a courtesy notice to let the author know that their work was eligible for deletion and at what time (and that they should save or otherwise utilize any responses they got), rather than staff just wiping out stuff without letting the author know.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>is there a statistics on the percentage of articles that survive the 24-hour period? That would help discuss the matter properly.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I don't think these stats exist? The closest you might be able to get is looking at the works that have deletion timers that were cleared, but combing through discussions to find that would be a colossal time commitment.</p>
<p>Plenty of authors prefer to self-delete and work on something at their own pace rather than scramble to beat the deletion timer. Some authors even take down the work within a few hours of initial posting, if it falls into the negatives (even before -10).</p>
<p>Additionally, page rewrites happen a fair bit, and the deletion of the original page is allowed to give the rewrite author a clean slate to work with. As far as I know, most people who request rewrites of a newly-posted page just let the deletion timer elapse as usual, and post their rewrite version on their own time.</p>
</div>
