<blockquote>
<p>is there a statistics on the percentage of articles that survive the 24-hour period? That would help discuss the matter properly.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Not that I've seen, though individual discussion threads would show an aborted deletion counter in that scenario. I can recall only seeing a handful of those, which puts a &quot;successful turnaround&quot; rating as <em>significantly less</em> than 1%.</p>
<p>And in those scenarios that I recall, they were typically at an &quot;almost there&quot; state, where simple fixes or the addition/removal of certain elements had a drastic impact on the overall quality of the SCP. In one case, the fix was to make it a -J, while another was to resubmit it as a non 001 proposal. Many SCPs that hit -10 or more cannot be so easily fixed; they tend to have significant portions of the article itself that needs to be completely overhauled, the subject is lackluster and needs more thought put into it at a fundamental level, or the writer is attempting a subject matter that is simply beyond their skill to execute properly.</p>
<p>Regardless, as Zyn mentioned, the 24 hour grace period isn't generally there for the author to try and save it (though they're welcome to try if they have a good idea how to fix it), but as a courtesy so the author knows that their SCP is going to be removed for, effectively, having insufficient quality.</p>

