			<div class="content" id="post-content-4810905">
									

<blockquote>
<p>I don't really see any harm in posting the Sandbox, especially if the author feels more comfortable with it than summarizing as a proposal.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Reviewers in the concept critique forum are present to critique concepts, not drafts. The point of having the &quot;only provide a sandbox link if asked&quot; rule is to ensure that authors don't inadvertently make it more difficult for reviewers to assist them.</p>
<p>If a reviewer has a question about the basic premise of a piece, it's much more conducive to the review process if the author can quickly and directly answer said question, rather than the author just having the reviewer dig through the entirety of a draft to maybe (not always, in the case of drafts with many errors or written unclearly) find clues.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I tend to write my SCP idea as a Sandbox before making a proposal for it, so I feel like that my &quot;summary&quot; of my SCP idea may not be as good as the Sandbox.</p>
