<p>I mean, technically a necropost, but I think the main concern here is that given how long this first page of comments is, your comment is a lot more lost here than it would have been if you made a New Post in this thread and not a reply.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>nothing at all with regards to feedback since maybe a week after posting, so I have no clue what's making it so hit-or-miss</p>
</blockquote>
<p>New articles lose their extra attention after a couple days unless they're particularly enjoyable, so it's fairly common for articles in the single-digit ratings to get buried. Given the sheer number of new posts we get every day, it can be hard to hold the audience's attention as new things come in. Most people just move on after they comment, since they're there to be entertained and don't necessarily want to be obligated to stick around to help further. No one gets paid for the work they put into the site, as it is.</p>
<p>We do have the Young and Under 30 project, which tries to shed more light on articles that wind up kind of unattended: <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/young-and-under-30">http://www.scp-wiki.net/young-and-under-30</a></p>
<p>That said, you can always try using the feedback you did receive to come up with a rewrite, and then post that to Drafts and Critiques/the chat. Using the chatroom is probably your best bet when it comes to getting responses, since chat is real-time and a lot more people hang out in chat than in the forums.</p>

