															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/oz-ouroboros" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1743859); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1743859&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251577" alt="OZ Ouroboros" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1743859)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/oz-ouroboros" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1743859); return false;" >OZ Ouroboros</a></span> <span class="odate time_1499731863 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">11 Jul 2017 00:11</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3177479">
									

<p>The rules are fine, but lately I've felt uncomfortable writing due to fear of being ostracized by the community. Weryllium and I briefly talked about a &quot;shadow list&quot; of topics that are considered to be sketchy/tiptoey areas for one reason or another. I realize we have a wide spectrum of different backgrounds/ideals in this community, but I've seen multiple instances where the staff/userbase, in my opinion, were <em>way</em> too enthusiastic in dishing out punishment for something they considered to be in poor taste. A large portion of these punishments were towards the new members, who don't quite know the ropes yet. As the saying goes, they got tossed out of the frying pan, and into the fire of what I'll call a mob mentality.</p>
<p>Those new members were probably scared/bewildered when they were dogpiled; I know I'd be if I was still that non-accustomed, and things were probably only made worse when the staff decided to enact a ban. I honestly think we have to be a bit more lenient when it comes to the prospect of dealing with mistakes. I think that's one of the reasons outside communities think of us as elitists, because we are quick to pounce on things we deem &quot;inappropriate&quot;, even if such &quot;inppropriateness&quot; was due to simple mistakes/early jitters. It's one thing for a small group to sigh and say &quot;tough love&quot; and then hug it out the next day. It's another for a large group to blanket party someone, say &quot;tough shit&quot;, and then expect all to be forgiven the next time you see them.</p>
<p>After seeing so many newbies get flagged on the SCP Watchlist, I've honestly felt myself feeling not as inclined to write as I did before. I've been here for nearly four years, but now, if I had to sum up my feelings about my stance on writing more, it would be&#8230; afraid. And that's odd and troubling to me, coming from a guy who now has one Skip in the 500's and several more in the 100's after. I'm afraid I'm gonna slip up and not quite make the community's cut on something I write. I'm afraid I'm going to be attacked/flagged for being inappropriate when I really wasn't trying to be. Writing isn't as fun for me anymore, because nowadays, I'm less concerned about how good of a story I can make, and more concerned about who I might possibly offend. And that's really put a wet towel on my fire.</p>

							</div>

								
					
