														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3178392">
									

<p>You are free to state your view accordingly, as that's entirely part of the critique process.</p>
<p>My concern lies more in with Weryl's example, when people jump the gun and immediately label their fellow users as not only a bad writer, but a bad person.</p>
<p>Here's my own hypothetical.</p>
<p>I am writing a story about a Task Force members. One of the members happens to be gay/lesbian. During one of their missions, that particular member is interrogating a suspect. Said suspect proceeds to call that member a slur of some sort or another in their anger/outrage. I myself am immediately called out for being &quot;homophobic&quot; and &quot;incapable of writing/should not be allowed to write about a character in a homosexual relationship&quot;, for using a slur which, in that setting, may be expected. <em>(In no way is it right, but it may happen.)</em></p>
<p>Another example. I am writing a Skip about WW2, where a group of American Soldiers come across the Japanese with the Skip in question. If I use the term &quot;Jap&quot;/&quot;Nip&quot; in the American's dialogue, am I immediately racist? No, I don't think so <em>(I myself am also part Japanese, so I wouldn't use this term normally.)</em>, but in the setting and time period, they were common terminology. Take a look at the Looney Tunes episode that is literally titled &quot;Bugs Bunny Nips the Nips&quot;.</p>
<p>There's a disconnect here that needs to be addressed. Death of the author if you will. I am not homophobic, and I am not racist. The character's words in no way reflect my views on the subject matter, at all. If the characters were poorly written, then yes, there would be cause for critique about how the dialogue was bad, or how the characterization needed work. But bad writing does not automatically equal bad person. There is a difference between saying &quot;I dislike the use of this racist term&quot; and saying &quot;You [the author] are racist.&quot;</p>

							</div>

								
