<p>Well it probably is a reasonable statement that some topics do require delicacy and sometimes authors don't demonstrate the maturity required. For example attempts to make jokes entirely based on stereotypes or slurs aren't likely to work. The examples you give, in the hands of a writer of your ability, aren't like that.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>There's a disconnect here that needs to be addressed. Death of the author if you will. I am not homophobic, and I am not racist. The character's words in no way reflect my views on the subject matter, at all. If the characters were poorly written, then yes, there would be cause for critique about how the dialogue was bad, or how the characterization needed work. But bad writing does not automatically equal bad person. There is a difference between saying &quot;I dislike the use of this racist term&quot; and saying &quot;You [the author] are racist.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Yes, I agree with this wholeheartedly. I try to make an effort myself to say things like &quot;this comes across as racist and isn't likely to work here&quot;. It works the other way too, there is an article that I am certain the author didn't intend it to come across the way that it does to me, and I don't have any particular dislike for them specifically, but I despise that article. Don't ever critique the author, critique the work. Which by the way <em>is</em> in the rules.</p>

