														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3178897">
									

<blockquote>
<p>Well it probably is a reasonable statement that some topics do require delicacy and sometimes authors don't demonstrate the maturity required.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I agree. But the community as a whole needs to work on being less 0 to 60 with the newbies. They are quite literally the next generation of potential writers we'll have. I see newbies get ripped apart and in turn do the ripping to the next wave <em>(Again with the mob mentality of being in the right)</em>. The cycle of &quot;I've been here longer than you so my advice is immediately good/better than yours&quot; needs to stop. <em>(This is an issue I see more with the people of a few months old rather than veterans with a few years under their belt.)</em></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Don't ever critique the author, critique the work. Which by the way <em>is</em> in the rules.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>As a whole, it definitely is, but back to Weryl's account as an example, like any rule, it can be overlooked, skipped <em>(Again with jumping the gun)</em>, or sidestepped. In the case of sidestepping one of the things that really grinds my gears is when I see so-called &quot;critiques&quot; that are really just snide underhanded digs rather than actual feedback <em>(I sense we're going into a whole different discussion here though, so that'll be a story for another time.)</em> Behavior like this, especially with staff, is concerning. <em>(I understand staff deals with this internally, but when incidents such as that are public, it puts the community in a bad light.)</em></p>

							</div>

								
					
